\pard\fs20 Murray Templeton was forty-five years old, in the prime of life, and with all parts of his body in perfect working order except for certain key portions of his coronary arteries, but that was enough.\par
\pard\fi288 The pain had come suddenly, had mounted to an unbearable peak, and had then ebbed steadily.  He could feel his breath slowing and a kind of gathering peace washing over him.\par
There is no pleasure like the absence of pain - immediately after pain.  Murray felt an almost giddy lightness as though he were lifting in the air and hovering.\par
He opened his eyes and noted with distant amusement that the others in the room were still agitated.  He had been in the laboratory when the pain had struck, quite without warning, and when he had staggered, he had heard surprised outcries from the others before everything vanished into overwhelming agony.\par
Now, with the pain gone, the others were still hovering, still anxious, still gathered about his fallen body -\par
- Which, he suddenly realised, he was looking down on.\par
He was down there, sprawled, face contorted.  He was up here, at peace and watching.\par
He thought: Miracle of miracles!  The life-after-life nuts were right.\par
And although that was a humiliating way for an atheistic physicist to die, he felt only the mildest surprise, and no alteration of the peace in which he was immersed.\par
He thought: There should be some angel - or something - coming for me.\par
The Earthly scene was fading.  Darkness was invading his consciousness and off in a distance, as a last glimmer of sight, there was a figure of light, vaguely human in form, and radiating warmth.\par
Murray thought: What a joke on me.  I\rquote m going to Heaven.\par
Even as he thought that, the light faded, but the warmth remained.  There was no lessening of the peace even though in all the Universe only he remained - and the Voice.\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote I have done this so often and yet I still have the capacity to be pleased at success.\rdblquote\par
It was in Murray\rquote s mind to say something, but he was not conscious of possessing a mouth, tongue, or vocal chords.  Nevertheless, tried to make a sound.  He tried, mouthlessly, to hum words or breathe them or just push them out by a contraction of - something.\par
And they came out.  He heard his own voice, quite recognisable, and his own words, infinitely clear.\par
Murray said, \ldblquote Is this Heaven?\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote This is no place as you understand place.\rdblquote\par
Murray was embarrassed, but the next question had to be asked.  \ldblquote Pardon me if I sound like a jackass.  Are you God?\rdblquote\par
Without changing intonation or in any way marring the perfection of the sound, the Voice managed to sound amused.  \ldblquote It is strange that I am always asked that in, of course, an infinite number of ways.  There is no answer I can give that you would comprehend.  I \i am\i0  - which is all that I can say significantly and you may cover that with any word or concept you please.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote And what am I?  A soul?  Or am I only personified existence too?\rdblquote   He tried not to sound sarcastic, but it seemed to him that he had failed.  He thought then, fleetingly, of adding a \lquote Your Grace\rquote  or \lquote Holy One\rquote  or \i something\i0  to counteract the sarcasm, and could not bring himself to do so even though for the first time in his existence he speculated on the possibility of being punished for his insolence - or sin? - with Hell, and what that might be like.\par
The Voice did not sound offended.  \ldblquote You are easy to explain - even to you.  You may call yourself a soul if that pleases you, but what you are is a nexus of electromagnetic forces, so arranged that all the interconnections and interrelationships are exactly imitative of those of your brain in your Universe-existence - down to the smallest detail.  Therefore you have your capacity for thought, your memories, your personality.  It still seems to you that you are you.\rdblquote\par
Murray found himself incredulous.  \ldblquote You mean the essence of my brain was permanent?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not at all.  There is nothing about you that is permanent except what I choose to make so.  I formed the nexus.  I constructed it while you had physical existence and adjusted it to the moment when the existence failed.\rdblquote\par
The Voice seemed distinctly pleased with itself, and went on after a moment\rquote s pause.  \ldblquote An intricate but entirely precise construction.  I could, of course, do it for every human being on your world but I am pleased that I do not.  There is pleasure in the selection.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You choose very few then?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very few.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what happens to the rest?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oblivion! - Oh, of course, you imagine a Hell.\rdblquote\par
Murray would have flushed if he had the capacity to do so.  He said, \ldblquote\i I\i0  do not.  It is spoken of.  Still, I would scarcely have thought I was virtuous enough to have attracted your attention as one of the Elect.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Virtuous? - Ah, I see what you mean.  It is troublesome to have to force my thinking small enough to permeate yours.  No, I have chosen you for your capacity for thought, as I choose others, in quadrillions, from all the intelligent species of the Universe.\rdblquote\par
Murray found himself suddenly curious, the habit of a lifetime.  He said, \ldblquote Do you choose them all yourself or are there others like you?\rdblquote\par
For a fleeting moment, Murray thought there was an impatient reaction to that, but when the Voice came, it was unmoved.  \ldblquote Whether or not there are others is irrelevant to you.  This Universe is mine, and mine alone.  It is my invention, my construction, intended for my purpose alone.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And yet with quadrillions of nexi you have formed, you spend time with me?  Am I that important?\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote You are not important at all.  I am also with others in a way which, to your perception, would seem simultaneous.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And yet you are one?\rdblquote\par
Again amusement.  The Voice said, \ldblquote You seek to trap me into an inconsistency.  If you were an amoeba who could consider individuality only in connection with single cells and if you were to ask a sperm whale, made up of thirty quadrillion cells, whether it was one or many, how could the sperm whale answer in a way that would be comprehensible to the amoeba?\rdblquote\par
Murray said dryly, \ldblquote I\rquote ll think about it.  It may become comprehensible.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Exactly.  That is your function.  You will think.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To what end?  You already know everything, I suppose.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote Even if I knew everything, I could not know that I know everything.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote That sounds like a bit of Eastern philosophy - something that sounds profound precisely because it has no meaning.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote You have promise.  You answer my paradox with a paradox - except that mine is not a paradox.  Consider.  I have existed eternally, but what does that mean?  It means I cannot remember having come into existence.  If I could, I would not have existed eternally.  If I cannot remember having come into existence, then there is at least one thing - the nature of my coming into existence - that I do not know.\par
\ldblquote Then, too, although what I know is infinite, it is also true that what there is to know is infinite, and how can I be sure that both infinities are equal?  The infinity of potential knowledge may be infinitely greater than the infinity of my actual knowledge.  Here is a simple example: If I knew every one of the even integers, I would know an infinite number of items, and yet I would still not know a single odd integer.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote But the odd integers can be derived.  If you divide every even integer in the entire infinite series by two, you will get another infinite series which will contain within it the infinite series of odd integers.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote You have the idea.  I am pleased.  It will be your task to find other such ways, far more difficult ones, from the known to the not-yet-known.  You have your memories.  You will remember all the data you have ever collected or learned, or that you have or will deduce from that data.  If necessary, you will be allowed to learn what additional data you will consider relevant to the problems you set yourself.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Could you not do all that for yourself?\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote I can, but it is more interesting this way.  I constructed the Universe in order to have more facts to deal with.  I inserted the uncertainty principle, entropy, and other randomisation factors to make the whole not instantly obvious.  It has worked well for it has amused me throughout its entire existence.\par
\ldblquote I then allowed complexities that produced first life and then intelligence, and use it as a source for a research team, not because I need the aid, but because it would introduce a new random factor.  I found I could not predict the next interesting piece of knowledge gained, where it would come from, by what means derived.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote Does that ever happen?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly.  A century doesn\rquote t pass in which some interesting item doesn\rquote t appear somewhere.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Something that you could have thought of yourself, but had not done so yet?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote Do you actually think there\rquote s a chance of \i my\i0  obliging you in this manner?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In the next century?  Virtually none.  In the long run, though, your success is certain, since you will be engaged eternally.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote I will be thinking through eternity?  Forever?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To what end?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I have told you.  To find new knowledge.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But beyond that.  For what purpose am I to find new knowledge?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was what you did in your Universe-bound life.  What was its purpose then?\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote To gain new knowledge that only I could gain.  To receive the praise of my fellows.  To feel the satisfaction of accomplishment knowing that I had only a short time allotted me for the purpose. - Now I would gain only what you could gain yourself if you wished to take a small bit of trouble.  You cannot praise me; you can only be amused.  And there is no credit or satisfaction in accomplishment when I have all eternity to do it in.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote And you do not find thought and discovery worthwhile in itself?  You do not find it requiring no further purpose?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote For a finite time, yes.  Not for all eternity.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see your point.  Nevertheless, you have no choice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You say I am to think.  You cannot make me do so.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote I do not wish to constrain you directly.  I will not need to.  Since you can do nothing but think, you will think.  You do not know how not to think.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then I will give myself a goal.  I will invent a purpose.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said tolerantly, \ldblquote That you can certainly do.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I have already found a purpose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote May I know what it is?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know already.  I know we are not speaking in the ordinary fashion.  You adjust my nexus is such a way that I believe I hear you and I believe I speak, but you transfer thoughts to me and from me directly.  And when my nexus changes with my thoughts you are at once aware of them and do not need my voluntary transmission.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote You are surprisingly correct.  I am pleased. - But it also pleases me to have you tell me your thoughts voluntarily.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then I will tell you.  The purpose of my thinking will be to discover a way to disrupt this nexus of me that you have created.  I do not want to think for no purpose but to amuse you.  I do not want to think forever to amuse you.  I do not want to exist forever to amuse you.  All my thinking will be directed toward ending the nexus.  \i That\i0  would amuse \i me\i0 .\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote I have no objection to that.  Even concentrated thought on ending your own existence may, in spite of you, come up with something new and interesting.  And, of course, if you succeed in this suicide attempt you will have accomplished nothing, for I would instantly reconstruct you and in such a way as to make your method of suicide impossible.  And if you found another and still more subtle fashion of disrupting yourself, I would reconstruct you with that possibility eliminated, and so on.  It could be an interesting game, but you will nevertheless exist eternally.  It is my will.\rdblquote\par
Murray felt a quaver but the words came out with a perfect calm.  \ldblquote Am I in Hell then, after all?  You have implied there is none, but if this were Hell you would lie to us as part of the game of Hell.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote In that case, of what use is it to assure you that you are not in Hell?  Nevertheless, I assure you.  There is here neither Heaven nor Hell.  There is only myself.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote Consider, then, that my thoughts may be useless to you.  If I come up with nothing useful, will it not be worth your while to - disassemble me and take no further trouble with me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote As a reward?  You want Nirvana as the prize of failure and you intend to assure me failure?  There is no bargain there.  You will not fail.  With all eternity before you, you cannot avoid having at least one interesting thought, however you try against it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then I will create another purpose for myself.  I will not try to destroy myself.  I will set as my goal the humiliation of you.  I will think of something you have not only never thought of but never could think of.  I will think of the last answer, beyond which there is no knowledge further.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote You do not understand the nature of the infinite.  There may be things I have not yet troubled to know.  There cannot be anything I cannot know.\rdblquote\par
Murray said thoughtfully, \ldblquote You cannot know your beginning.  You have said so.  Therefore you cannot know your end.  Very well, then.  That will be my purpose and that will be the last answer.  I will not destroy myself.  I will destroy \i you\i0  - if you do not destroy me first.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, \ldblquote Ah!  You come to that in rather less than average time.  I would have thought it would have taken you longer.  There is not one of those I have with me in this existence of perfect and eternal thought that does not have the ambition of destroying me.  It cannot be done.\rdblquote\par
Murray said, \ldblquote I have all eternity to think of a way of destroying you.\rdblquote\par
The Voice said, equably, \ldblquote Then try to think of it.\rdblquote   And it was gone.\par
But Murray had his purpose now and was content.\par
For what could \i any\i0  Entity, conscious of eternal existence, want - but an end?\par
For what else had the Voice been searching for countless billions of years?  And for what other reason had intelligence been created and certain specimens salvaged and put to work, but to aid in that great search?  And Murray intended that it would be he, and he alone, who would succeed.\par
Carefully, and with the thrill of purpose, Murray began to think.\par
He had plenty of time.\par
